STORET Definition: The user-defined code that uniquely identifies an Organization. Organization IDs are registered centrally with STORET so that they are guaranteed to be unique on the National level. They become part of the Oracle Key on every row in the STORET database that belongs to the Organization.
BIODATA EDSC Definition: A designator used to uniquely identify a unique business establishment within a context.

STORET Definition: The formal full-length name of the Organization.
BIODATA EDSC Definition: The legal designator (i.e. formal name) of an organization.

STORET Definition: The text describing details of the Organization that users may wish to provide. For example, this text may be used to describe the purpose, mission, or goals of the Organization.
BIODATA EDSC Compliance: Business Decision: No corresponding element found in EDSC standards.

STORET Definition: The code that describes the type of Organization.
BIODATA EDSC Definition: The code that represents the American Indian tribe or Alaskan Native entity.

STORET Definition: Text or codes which are used to specify an Electronic Address for an Organization or an individual.
BIODATA EDSC Definition: A resource address, usually consisting of the access protocol, the domain name, and optionally, the path to a file or location.

STORET Definition: The code designating the type of Electronic Address.
BIODATA EDSC Definition: The name that describes the electronic address type.

STORET Definition: Text or codes which are used to specify an Electronic Address for an Organization or an individual.
BIODATA EDSC Definition: The number that identifies a particular telephone connection.

STORET Definition: The code designating the type of Electronic Address.
BIODATA EDSC Definition: The name that describes a telephone number type.
The number assigned within an organization to an individual telephone that extends the external telephone number.

STORET Definition: The code designating the type of Address.
BIODATA EDSC Compliance: Business Decision: No corresponding element found in EDSC standards.

STORET Definition:
The first line of an Address which usually denotes the company or individual name.
AND
The second line of an Address usually denotes the mail routing code, p.o. box number, or suite but can also contain company name in addition.
BIODATA EDSC Definition:
"The exact address where a mail piece is intended to be delivered, including urban-style street address, rural route, and PO Box"
or
"The address that describes the physical (geographic) location of the front door or main entrance of a facility site, including urban-style street address or rural address."
BIODATA EDSC Compliance: Business Decision: WQX exchange did not want duplicate elements to track mailing and location addresses and thus combined them using an AddressType desgnator.

STORET Definition:
The second line of an Address usually denotes the mail routing code, p.o. box number, or suite but can also contain company name in addition.
AND
The third line of an Address usually denotes the street address including street name and type, house/office number, or sector designation.
BIODATA EDSC Definition:
The text that provides additional information about a place, including a building name with its secondary unit and number, an industrial park name, an installation name or descriptive text where no formal address is available.
Or
The text that provides additional information to facilitate the delivery of a mail piece, including building name, secondary units, and mail stop or local box numbers not serviced by the U.S. Postal Service.
BIODATA EDSC Compliance: Business Decision: WQX exchange did not want duplicate elements to track mailing and location addresses and thus combined them using an AddressType desgnator.

STORET Definition: The name of the city, state, and zip code in an Address.
BIODATA EDSC Definition:
The name of the city, town, or village where the mail is delivered.
Or
The name of the city, town, village or other locality, when identifiable, within whose boundaries (the majority of) the facility site is located. This is not always the same as the city used for USPS mail delivery.
BIODATA EDSC Compliance: Business Decision: WQX exchange did not want duplicate elements to track mailing and location addresses and thus combined them using an AddressType desgnator.

STORET Definition: The name of the city, state, and zip code in an Address.
BIODATA EDSC Definition: A code designator used to identify a principal administrative subdivision of the United States, Canada, or Mexico.

STORET Definition: The name of the city, state, and zip code in an Address.
BIODATA EDSC Definition: The combination of the 5-digit Zone Improvement Plan (ZIP) code and the four-digit extension code (if available) that represents the geographic segment that is a subunit of the ZIP Code, assigned by the U.S. Postal Service to a geographic location to facilitate mail delivery; or the postal zone specific to the country, other than the U.S., where the mail is delivered.
BIODATA EDSC Compliance: Business Decision: WQX exchange did not want duplicate elements to track mailing and location addresses and thus combined them using an AddressType desgnator.

STORET Definition: The code for the country in an Address.

BIODATA EDSC Data Element:
Detection Limit Type 
or
Reporting Limit Type
BIODATA EDSC Definition:
One of a list of client, regulation, or organization defined acronyms or statistic methodologies that specify the type of detection limit used for analysis. 
Or
One of a list of client, regulation, or organization defined acronyms or statistical methodologies that specify the type of reporting limit.
BIODATA EDSC Compliance: Business Decision: ESAR uses Detection Limit and Reporting Limit as separate fields. The team decided to combine these into 1 field that could be reported multiple times for each result to simplify the reporting process. A type field is then used to distinguish the type of detection or reporting condition reported.

STORET Definition:
Represents the least amount of the target substance which could be detected by the instrument/analytical process employed to determine the result. Above this value the target substance is presumed to be present.
OR
Represents the largest amount of the target substance which could be quantified by the instrument/analytical process employed to
determine the result. Values above the minimum and below the maximum quantitation limits are reported as valid numeric results.
OR
Represents the least amount of the target substance which could be quantified by the instrument/analytical process employed to
determine the result. Values above the minimum and below the maximum quantitation limits are reported as valid numeric results.
BIODATA EDSC Data Element:
Detection Limit / Measure Value 
or
Reporting Limit / Measure Value
BIODATA EDSC Definition:
Constituent concentration that produces a signal sufficiently greater than the blank and can be detected within specified levels by good laboratories during routine operating conditions.
OR
Constituent concentration that, when processed through the complete method, produces a signal that is statistically different from a blank.
BIODATA EDSC Compliance: Business Decision: ESAR uses Detection Limit and Reporting Limit as separate fields. The team decided to combine these into 1 field that could be reported multiple times for each result to simplify the reporting process. A type field is then used to distinguish the type of detection or reporting condition reported.

STORET Definition: The foreign key to TSRUOM implements "One Unit of Measure may qualify one or more detection/quantitation limits."
BIODATA EDSC Data Element:
Detection Limit / Measure Unit Code 
or
Reporting Limit / Measure Unit Code
BIODATA EDSC Definition: The code that represents the unit for measuring the item.
BIODATA EDSC Compliance: Business Decision: ESAR uses Detection Limit and Reporting Limit as separate fields. The team decided to combine these into 1 field that could be reported multiple times for each result to simplify the reporting process. A type field is then used to distinguish the type of detection or reporting condition reported.
